{
  "patch_id": "espressif-esp32-family-bootstrap-v1",
  "multicore_topology": {
    "topology": "xtensa-asymmetric-dual-core",
    "core_count": 2,
    "app_cpu_control_plane": {
      "register": "DPORT.APPCPU_CTRL_B",
      "operation": "set-bit-0",
      "start_vector_symbol": "_vectors_cpu1"
    }
  },
  "__source_notes": {
    "io_matrix_reference": "esp-idf/components/soc/esp32/include/soc/gpio_sig_map.h",
    "io_matrix_comment": "Pin signal AF numbers (IO Matrix indices) are deferred to a follow-on; this bootstrap leaves pin_signals empty and lets the ESP32 device IR carry pins without IO Matrix routing — same posture the ESP32-S3 took initially.",
    "dual_core_perspective": "ESP32 is a dual-core Xtensa LX6 SoC; the runtime startup emitter generates dual vector tables, two Reset_Handler entry points, and a bring_up_app_cpu() primitive that pokes DPORT.APPCPU_CTRL_B.  Affinity routing of individual interrupts and inter-core synchronization primitives are out of scope for the bootstrap contract — those are esp-idf concerns.",
    "svd_coverage_note": "espressif/svd/esp32.svd ships a partial peripheral catalogue; UART1/UART2, SPI2/SPI3, I2C1, TIMG1 exist in hardware but only their CLK_EN bits inside DPORT are present in the SVD.  The bootstrap admits only the peripherals the SVD declares as top-level instances; a follow-on can extend the device patch with manual peripheral declarations to cover the missing instances.",
    "__readme_caveat": "Upstream `espressif/svd/esp32.svd` is partial — UART1/UART2, SPI2/SPI3, I2C1, TIMG1 only exist as DPORT clock-gate bits.  Dual-core control plane is emitted (PRO_CPU + APP_CPU bring-up via `bring_up_app_cpu()`); affinity routing and inter-core IPC delegate to esp-idf.  ADC factory calibration (eFuse-stored characterization curve) is also delegated to esp-idf's `esp_adc_cal_*` runtime API; the ADC trait carries register references and resolution options but `kCalibrationContext.valid=false`."
  },
